# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
"""Places batch D: Pushkar/Ajmer, Bikaner, Mount Abu, Bundi, Shekhawati & wildlife parks."""
POSTS = []
def P(**k): POSTS.append(k)

# ---- PUSHKAR & AJMER ----

P(slug="pushkar-lake", city="Pushkar", region="Ajmer", cat="Lake & Ghat",
  name="Pushkar Lake", query="Pushkar Lake",
  excerpt="One of India's most sacred lakes, ringed by 52 ghats and 400 temples — the spiritual heart of the holy town of Pushkar.",
  tags=["Pushkar","lake","pilgrimage","ghats"],
  info=dict(timings="Ghats open all day; aarti at sunset", entry="Free (note: 'Pushkar passport' flower-offering scams occur — be aware)",
            best="Sunset aarti; or the Pushkar Camel Fair (Nov)", duration="1–2 hours", reach="Town centre of Pushkar, ~15 km from Ajmer"),
  body="""<p>The little town of Pushkar wraps around one of the holiest lakes in India — a sacred body of water said to have formed where a lotus fell from the hand of Lord Brahma. Its 52 ghats and some 400 temples draw pilgrims year-round to bathe in the waters and offer prayers.</p>
<p>The atmosphere is unlike anywhere else in Rajasthan: part pilgrimage site, part bohemian traveller haven, with a bustling bazaar, rooftop cafés and a laid-back, spiritual air. The evening aarti at the ghats, with lamps floating on the water, is deeply atmospheric.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The sunset aarti at the ghats.</li><li>The rare Brahma Temple, one of very few in the world.</li><li>The colourful Pushkar bazaar and rooftop cafés.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Be aware of the 'Pushkar passport' scam, where visitors are pressured into paid flower offerings at the ghats — a polite, firm no works. Remove shoes and dress respectfully near the water. The November Camel Fair is a spectacular (and crowded) time to visit.</p>""")

P(slug="brahma-temple-pushkar", city="Pushkar", region="Ajmer", cat="Temple",
  name="Brahma Temple", query="Brahma Temple Pushkar",
  excerpt="One of the only temples in the world dedicated to Lord Brahma, the creator — the spiritual centrepiece of Pushkar.",
  tags=["Pushkar","temple","pilgrimage","rare"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 6 AM – 1:30 PM & 3 PM – 8:30 PM", entry="Free",
            best="Early morning", duration="30–45 minutes", reach="A short walk from Pushkar Lake in the town centre"),
  body="""<p>Temples to Brahma, the Hindu god of creation, are extraordinarily rare — and the Jagatpita Brahma Mandir at Pushkar is the most important of the very few that exist. That rarity makes it one of the most significant pilgrimage sites in the country.</p>
<p>Marked by its distinctive red spire and a hamsa (goose) motif, the temple is built of marble and stone, its silver-coin-studded floor worn smooth by centuries of devotees. Set close to the sacred lake, it forms the spiritual anchor of the whole town.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The rare four-faced image of Brahma in the sanctum.</li><li>The silver turtle and coin-inlaid marble floor.</li><li>The red-spired exterior with its goose emblem.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Photography inside is restricted and shoes must be left outside. It's a short walk from the ghats — visit the two together.</p>""")

P(slug="ajmer-sharif-dargah", city="Ajmer", region="Ajmer", cat="Temple",
  name="Ajmer Sharif Dargah", query="Ajmer Sharif Dargah",
  excerpt="One of the most revered Sufi shrines in the world — the tomb of Khwaja Moinuddin Chishti, drawing pilgrims of all faiths.",
  tags=["Ajmer","Sufi","pilgrimage","dargah"],
  info=dict(timings="Open early morning to late night (varies by season)", entry="Free",
            best="Evening for the qawwali; Urs festival is the peak", duration="1–2 hours", reach="Old city of Ajmer, ~130 km from Jaipur"),
  body="""<p>The Ajmer Sharif Dargah is among the holiest Sufi shrines on earth — the resting place of the revered 13th-century saint Khwaja Moinuddin Chishti. For over 800 years, pilgrims of every faith have travelled here to seek blessings, making it one of India's most powerful symbols of shared devotion.</p>
<p>The complex, with its silver gates, marble courtyards and great domed tomb, hums with constant activity — the scent of roses, the offering of chadars, and above all the soul-stirring qawwali music sung at the shrine. During the annual Urs festival, it draws vast crowds from across the subcontinent.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The main shrine and the offering of a rose-petal chadar.</li><li>The evening qawwali (devotional Sufi music).</li><li>The huge ceremonial cooking cauldrons (degs) in the courtyard.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Cover your head before entering (cloths are available), and be prepared for large crowds and narrow, busy approach lanes. Guardians may offer to help with offerings — agree any amount clearly beforehand.</p>""")

# ---- BIKANER ----

P(slug="junagarh-fort-bikaner", city="Bikaner", region="Thar", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Junagarh Fort", query="Junagarh Fort Bikaner",
  excerpt="A rare Rajasthan fort built on the plains, not a hill — and one of the best preserved, with sumptuous painted palaces inside.",
  tags=["fort","Bikaner","museum","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="10 AM – 5:30 PM (daily)", entry="Approx ₹50 (Indian) / ₹300 (foreign, incl. audio guide)",
            best="Morning", duration="2 hours", reach="Bikaner city centre"),
  body="""<p>Unusually for Rajasthan, Junagarh Fort was built not on a hilltop but on the flat desert plains — and defended so well by its moat and walls that it was never conquered. Begun in 1589, it has survived the centuries remarkably intact, and its interiors are among the most sumptuous in the state.</p>
<p>Behind the imposing exterior lies a series of exquisite palaces, courtyards and pavilions decorated with intricate paintings, mirror-work, gold leaf and carved stone. The Anup Mahal, Phool Mahal and Chandra Mahal show Rajput craftsmanship at its most lavish.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The opulent Anup Mahal with its gold-and-red decoration.</li><li>The mirror-work and painted chambers throughout.</li><li>The vintage aircraft and royal collections in the museum.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The audio guide adds a lot to the visit. Bikaner is off the main tourist trail, so the fort is often pleasantly uncrowded. Don't leave town without trying its famous namkeen (savoury snacks) and sweets.</p>""")

P(slug="karni-mata-temple-deshnoke", city="Deshnoke", region="Thar", cat="Temple",
  name="Karni Mata Temple (Rat Temple)", query="Karni Mata Temple Deshnoke",
  excerpt="The extraordinary 'Temple of Rats' — where thousands of sacred rats are revered and protected as holy.",
  tags=["Bikaner","temple","offbeat","unique"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 4 AM – 10 PM", entry="Free (camera charge applies)",
            best="Early morning or evening", duration="45 minutes (plus drive)", reach="Deshnoke, ~30 km south of Bikaner"),
  body="""<p>One of the most unusual temples in the world sits in the town of Deshnoke, near Bikaner. The Karni Mata Temple is home to some 25,000 sacred rats — known as kabas — who scurry freely across its marble floors and are worshipped and protected as holy, believed to be reincarnated devotees of the goddess Karni Mata.</p>
<p>Behind an ornate silver gate and marble façade, the temple is a genuinely singular experience: pilgrims move barefoot among the rats, and spotting one of the rare white rats is considered especially auspicious. It's a striking testament to India's diversity of belief.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The sacred rats moving freely through the temple.</li><li>The chance to spot a rare white rat (considered very lucky).</li><li>The beautifully carved silver doors and marble façade.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>You must go barefoot inside, as at any temple — a real test of nerve here. It's considered lucky if a rat runs over your feet. Not for the squeamish, but an unforgettable, respectful cultural experience.</p>""")

# ---- MOUNT ABU ----

P(slug="dilwara-temples-mount-abu", city="Mount Abu", region="Sirohi", cat="Temple",
  name="Dilwara Jain Temples", query="Dilwara Temples Mount Abu",
  excerpt="Possibly the most exquisite marble carving in India — five Jain temples whose ceilings defy belief.",
  tags=["Mount Abu","Jain","marble","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="Tourists usually 12 PM – 5 PM (mornings for worship)", entry="Free (photography not permitted inside)",
            best="Afternoon visiting hours", duration="1–1.5 hours", reach="~2.5 km from Mount Abu town centre"),
  body="""<p>Hidden in the hill station of Mount Abu — Rajasthan's only hill station — the Dilwara Temples are, for many, the finest example of marble craftsmanship anywhere in India. Built between the 11th and 13th centuries, this group of five Jain temples looks modest from outside, but the interiors are simply astonishing.</p>
<p>Every ceiling, pillar, arch and panel is carved from white marble into lace-like detail so fine that the stone seems almost translucent. The lotus-shaped central ceiling of the Vimal Vasahi temple is a particular masterpiece. Photography isn't allowed — you simply have to stand and marvel.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The impossibly intricate ceilings of the Vimal Vasahi and Luna Vasahi temples.</li><li>The carved marble pillars and the central lotus dome.</li><li>The serene, reverent atmosphere.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Tourists are admitted only in the afternoon, after morning worship. Photography, leather items and phones are not permitted inside. Dress modestly. It's the highlight of any Mount Abu visit.</p>""")

P(slug="nakki-lake-mount-abu", city="Mount Abu", region="Sirohi", cat="Lake & Ghat",
  name="Nakki Lake", query="Nakki Lake Mount Abu",
  excerpt="A pretty hill-station lake ringed by green hills and curious rock formations — the relaxed heart of Mount Abu.",
  tags=["Mount Abu","lake","hill station","boating"],
  info=dict(timings="Open all day; boating during daylight", entry="Free; boating charges apply",
            best="Sunset, from Sunset Point nearby", duration="1 hour", reach="In the centre of Mount Abu town"),
  body="""<p>At the heart of Mount Abu lies Nakki Lake, a tranquil body of water cradled by green hills at over 1,200 metres above sea level. As Rajasthan's only hill station, Mount Abu offers a cool, leafy respite from the desert plains, and the lake is its social centre.</p>
<p>Pedal-boats drift across the water, families stroll the shore, and curious rock formations — most famously the balancing Toad Rock — dot the surrounding hills. Nearby Sunset Point offers a classic end to the day.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>A pedal-boat ride on the lake.</li><li>The oddly shaped Toad Rock and other formations.</li><li>Sunset from the nearby Sunset Point.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Mount Abu is a popular summer escape, so it's busiest in the hot months. The cool climate is a welcome change — carry a light layer for the evenings.</p>""")

P(slug="guru-shikhar-mount-abu", city="Mount Abu", region="Sirohi", cat="Viewpoint",
  name="Guru Shikhar", query="Guru Shikhar Mount Abu",
  excerpt="The highest point in Rajasthan and the entire Aravalli range — sweeping views from a small hilltop temple.",
  tags=["Mount Abu","viewpoint","peak","nature"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 7 AM – 7 PM", entry="Free",
            best="Clear mornings for the views", duration="1 hour", reach="~15 km from Mount Abu town, near the highest Aravalli peak"),
  body="""<p>At just over 1,700 metres, Guru Shikhar is the highest peak in Rajasthan and in the whole Aravalli range — one of the oldest mountain systems on earth. A short climb from the road leads to a small temple dedicated to Dattatreya at the summit.</p>
<p>On a clear day the panorama is superb: the green folds of Mount Abu below, the plains stretching to the horizon, and a real sense of standing on the roof of the state. An old bell at the temple rings out across the hills.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The summit views across the Aravallis and plains.</li><li>The Dattatreya temple and its ancient bell.</li><li>The cool, fresh mountain air.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's a short but steep flight of steps to the top. Mornings usually offer the clearest views. Easily combined with the rest of a Mount Abu trip.</p>""")

# ---- BUNDI ----

P(slug="taragarh-fort-bundi", city="Bundi", region="Hadoti", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Taragarh Fort & Bundi Palace", query="Taragarh Fort Bundi",
  excerpt="A wonderfully atmospheric, half-wild hill fort above the blue town of Bundi — famed for its rare Rajput miniature murals.",
  tags=["fort","Bundi","murals","offbeat"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 8 AM – 5 PM", entry="Palace approx ₹100–₹200; fort largely open",
            best="Morning; October–March", duration="2–3 hours", reach="Above Bundi town, ~210 km from Jaipur / ~35 km from Kota"),
  body="""<p>Overlooked by the tourist crowds, the little blue town of Bundi is one of Rajasthan's most charming secrets — and its Taragarh Fort and adjoining palace are a big reason why. Clinging to a steep hillside, the fort is romantically overgrown and half-wild, with monkeys, sweeping views and an air of faded grandeur.</p>
<p>The real treasures are inside the Bundi Palace: the Chitrashala, a gallery of exquisite Rajput miniature murals in vivid blues and greens, considered among the finest surviving examples of the art form. Exploring here feels like genuine discovery.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The Chitrashala murals in the Bundi Palace.</li><li>The views over the blue town and Nawal Sagar lake.</li><li>The atmospheric, overgrown climb up to Taragarh.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Watch for monkeys on the way up. Bundi is refreshingly untouristy and best enjoyed slowly. It pairs well with the nearby stepwells and Kota.</p>""")

P(slug="raniji-ki-baori-bundi", city="Bundi", region="Hadoti", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Raniji Ki Baori (Stepwell)", query="Raniji ki Baori Bundi",
  excerpt="The 'Queen's Stepwell' — a magnificent 17th-century baori, the grandest of Bundi's famous stepwells.",
  tags=["Bundi","stepwell","architecture","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 8 AM – 6 PM", entry="Free / nominal",
            best="Morning light", duration="30–45 minutes", reach="In Bundi town centre"),
  body="""<p>Bundi is sometimes called the 'City of Stepwells', and the finest of them all is Raniji Ki Baori — the Queen's Stepwell — built in 1699. Descending over 45 metres into the ground, it's a breathtaking example of the water architecture that once sustained Rajasthan's desert towns.</p>
<p>A high, ornately carved arched gateway leads down flights of steps past sculpted pillars and niches holding images of deities. Cool, quiet and beautifully proportioned, it's a reminder of how these functional structures were elevated into genuine works of art.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The towering carved entrance arch.</li><li>The sculpted niches and pillars lining the descent.</li><li>Bundi's many other stepwells scattered through town.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's an easy stop in the middle of Bundi town. Combine it with the palace and a wander through the blue lanes for a lovely, low-key day.</p>""")

# ---- WILDLIFE & SHEKHAWATI ----

P(slug="ranthambore-national-park", city="Sawai Madhopur", region="Ranthambore", cat="Wildlife",
  name="Ranthambore National Park", query="Ranthambore National Park tiger",
  excerpt="Rajasthan's premier tiger reserve — where big cats roam among ancient ruins and a thousand-year-old fort.",
  tags=["wildlife","tiger","safari","national park"],
  info=dict(timings="Safaris in morning & afternoon slots (park closed monsoon, ~July–Sept)", entry="Safari packages (jeep/canter); book permits well ahead",
            best="October–April; April–May for higher tiger sightings", duration="Half day per safari (2–3 nights recommended)", reach="Near Sawai Madhopur, ~130 km from Jaipur (rail-connected)"),
  body="""<p>Ranthambore is Rajasthan's most famous wildlife destination and one of the best places in India to see a wild tiger. Once a royal hunting ground, the park spreads across dry forest, lakes and dramatic ruins, all watched over by the ancient Ranthambore Fort — a setting that makes a safari here uniquely cinematic.</p>
<p>Beyond its celebrated tigers, the park is home to leopards, sloth bears, crocodiles, deer, and a wealth of birdlife. Spotting a tiger padding past a crumbling chhatri or beside a misty lake is an experience that stays with you.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>A morning or afternoon jeep safari in search of tigers.</li><li>The atmospheric Ranthambore Fort within the reserve.</li><li>The lakes and their crocodiles, birds and deer.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Safari permits are limited and sell out — book well in advance, and do more than one safari to improve your chances. The park closes during the monsoon (roughly July–September). Jeeps (gypsies) offer a better experience than the larger canters.</p>""")

P(slug="keoladeo-bharatpur", city="Bharatpur", region="Braj", cat="Wildlife",
  name="Keoladeo National Park (Bharatpur)", query="Keoladeo National Park Bharatpur",
  excerpt="A UNESCO-listed wetland and one of the world's great bird sanctuaries — a paradise for hundreds of species.",
  tags=["wildlife","birds","UNESCO","wetland"],
  info=dict(timings="6 AM – 6 PM (approx; seasonal)", entry="Approx ₹75 (Indian) / ₹500 (foreign); cycle-rickshaw guides available",
            best="November–February for migratory birds", duration="Half day", reach="Bharatpur, near Agra; ~180 km from Jaipur"),
  body="""<p>A very different kind of wildlife experience, Keoladeo National Park — long known as Bharatpur Bird Sanctuary — is one of the finest bird habitats in the world and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. This man-made wetland, once a royal duck-hunting reserve, now shelters hundreds of resident and migratory bird species.</p>
<p>In winter the park fills with visitors from as far as Siberia and Central Asia — painted storks, cranes, eagles, kingfishers and countless waterfowl. Explored on foot, by bicycle or in a cycle-rickshaw with a trained naturalist, it's a serene, immersive escape into nature.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The migratory birds in peak winter season.</li><li>A cycle-rickshaw tour with a knowledgeable bird guide.</li><li>The peaceful walking and cycling trails through the wetland.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The trained rickshaw-pullers double as excellent bird guides — well worth it. Bring binoculars if you have them. It sits conveniently on the Jaipur–Agra route.</p>""")

P(slug="mandawa-shekhawati", city="Mandawa", region="Shekhawati", cat="Heritage Site",
  name="Mandawa (Shekhawati Havelis)", query="Mandawa Shekhawati haveli",
  excerpt="An open-air gallery of painted merchant mansions — the finest town in Shekhawati, the 'world's largest open-air art gallery'.",
  tags=["Shekhawati","haveli","frescoes","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="Town open all day; individual havelis vary", entry="Some havelis charge a small fee",
            best="Morning or late afternoon light on the frescoes", duration="Half day", reach="Shekhawati region, ~170 km from Jaipur / ~250 km from Delhi"),
  body="""<p>The Shekhawati region is often called the world's largest open-air art gallery, and the town of Mandawa is its jewel. In the 18th and 19th centuries, wealthy Marwari merchants built grand havelis here and covered them, inside and out, with vivid frescoes — and many still survive.</p>
<p>Wandering Mandawa's streets, you pass mansion after mansion painted with scenes of gods and legends, royal processions, and — charmingly — the new inventions of the age, from trains to gramophones to early cars, as imagined by artists who had often never seen them. It's a uniquely delightful place to explore on foot.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The elaborately frescoed façades and courtyards of the havelis.</li><li>The quirky paintings of trains, cars and European scenes.</li><li>Staying overnight in a heritage haveli hotel.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Some havelis are private homes or hotels; others charge a small entry fee — a local guide helps you find the best. Mandawa makes a great stop between Delhi/Jaipur and Bikaner.</p>""")
